These notes outline the requirements, calculations, and preliminary design concepts for a macadamia nut cracking tool. The goal is to create a device that allows users—particularly those with lower grip strength—to crack macadamia nuts safely and effectively.

Key Data and Requirements

Macadamia nut cracking force: 222.1 kg (≈ 18.54 kN)

Tool-generated cracking force target: 241 kg

Macadamia nut size range: 12–24 mm

Average grip strength of a 60–64-year-old woman: 17.2–31.0 kg

Weak subject chosen for accessibility: ≈ 17.0 kg

The tool must amplify a user-applied force of ~17 kg to reach the required cracking force.

Force Amplification

Objective

Find a lever design that increases a 17 kg input force to the required ~241 kg output force.

Calculation (as written in notes)

241 / 17 ≈ 14.17

A mechanical advantage of roughly 14–17× is needed.

Nut Placement and Dimensions

Nut diameter range: 12–24 mm

The nut should sit 12 mm from the pin.

Handle length and lever arm distances must be chosen to achieve the required mechanical advantage.

Example dimension from notes

Handle length: 170 mm from pin to handle center.

Nut distance from pin: 12 mm.

Mechanical advantage ≈ 170 / 12 ≈ 14.2 (matches required ratio).

Handle Design

Handle sketches indicate:

24 mm width

62 mm length in one sketch

12 mm thickness in another

Human hand clearance must be considered to avoid collision during operation.

Minimum travel distance required to crack nut: 5–7 mm.

Design Considerations

The same construction can be used for different nut sizes.

Angle of cracking may vary with nut size, but the general mechanism remains functional.

A major concern: if the nut is too small, the handle may collide with the user’s hand before completing the required travel.

Linear Actuator Option

Model: PA‑01

Voltage: 12 VDC or 24 VDC

Stroke: 1–40 inches

Force: 16–225 lbs

Price: ~$115–120 USD

This actuator could automate the cracking process.

Required actuator travel

Minimum travel: 5 mm

Handle travel: 75 mm (≈ 3 inches)

Additional Sketch Notes

Several hand-drawn diagrams indicate lever arms, handle geometry, and nut placement.

Dimensions such as 15 mm, 10 mm, and 24 mm appear in relation to handle and pin geometry.

Summary

These notes outline the early-stage design of a macadamia nut cracking tool using lever mechanics or a linear actuator. The key engineering requirement is achieving a mechanical advantage of approximately 14–17× so that a user with relatively low grip strength can still crack the nut. Dimensions and sketches suggest a compact lever-based device with careful attention to hand clearance and nut size variability.

